WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.004
( intro music )

00:00:10.343 --> 00:00:12.879
( applause )

00:00:12.879 --> 00:00:14.848
Thank you for coming
out tonight.

00:00:14.848 --> 00:00:16.415 line:0%
It's a great group.

00:00:16.415 --> 00:00:18.884 line:0%
And let's take a step

00:00:18.884 --> 00:00:20.619 line:0%
into my most favorite world,

00:00:20.619 --> 00:00:22.821
away from the world of
human beings,

00:00:22.821 --> 00:00:25.124
into the world of the jaguar.

00:00:25.124 --> 00:00:29.329
<i> I've been working on
 big cats and other species
 for over 30 years.</i>

00:00:29.329 --> 00:00:32.331
<i> But nothing in the
 tropical jungles</i>

00:00:32.331 --> 00:00:35.301
<i> has ever made my hair
 stand on end</i>

00:00:35.301 --> 00:00:37.169
<i> like one particular sound.</i>

00:00:37.169 --> 00:00:39.539
( Jaguar growl )
This is the guttural growl

00:00:39.539 --> 00:00:41.407
of the jaguar.

00:00:41.407 --> 00:00:43.810
This is saying stay away.

00:00:43.810 --> 00:00:45.845
You've wandered too close.

00:00:45.845 --> 00:00:49.348
I've heard that sound
five times in my life.

00:00:49.348 --> 00:00:51.417
And it's never gotten
any easier.

00:00:51.417 --> 00:00:54.053
( audience laughter )

00:00:54.053 --> 00:00:57.089
<i> The oldest jaguar we have
 on record</i>

00:00:57.089 --> 00:01:00.192
<i>is that of the European jaguar.</i>

00:01:00.192 --> 00:01:03.729
<i> In reaction to the
 Pleistocene ice ages</i>

00:01:03.729 --> 00:01:06.432
<i> started doing what we
 now know is</i>

00:01:06.432 --> 00:01:09.702
<i> a true characteristic
 of jaguars.</i>

00:01:09.702 --> 00:01:12.137
In response to adversity,

00:01:12.137 --> 00:01:15.474
in response to
environmental perturbations

00:01:15.474 --> 00:01:17.409
the jaguar moves.

00:01:17.409 --> 00:01:20.079
<i> And it moves, and it moves.</i>

00:01:20.079 --> 00:01:23.649
<i> Traveling thousands of miles
 eventually</i>

00:01:23.649 --> 00:01:25.451
<i> throughout the Pleistocene</i>

00:01:25.451 --> 00:01:28.354
<i> scattering in all directions.</i>

00:01:28.354 --> 00:01:30.656
<i> Now by the mid-Pleistocene</i>

00:01:30.656 --> 00:01:33.425
<i> the European jaguar
 went extinct.</i>

00:01:33.425 --> 00:01:36.095
The earliest evidence we have

00:01:36.095 --> 00:01:40.333
of early man and
jaguars together

00:01:40.333 --> 00:01:43.869
comes about
4,000 to 11,000 years ago

00:01:43.869 --> 00:01:46.806
where skeletons of early man
and jaguars

00:01:46.806 --> 00:01:48.942
are found in the same place.

00:01:48.942 --> 00:01:52.411
In a cave in Texas
called Schultz Cave.

00:01:52.411 --> 00:01:55.247
<i> There were at least
 12 civilizations</i>

00:01:55.247 --> 00:01:59.251
<i> going from Mexico
 into South America,</i>

00:01:59.251 --> 00:02:02.421
<i> but one of the
 earliest civilizations,</i>

00:02:02.421 --> 00:02:04.290
<i> and where what I call</i>

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:07.793
<i> the Jaguar Cultural Corridor
 was born</i>

00:02:07.793 --> 00:02:11.664
<i> was among a group of people
 called the Olmec.</i>

00:02:11.664 --> 00:02:13.198
One author who studied them

00:02:13.198 --> 00:02:15.267
called them "jaguar psychotics".

00:02:15.267 --> 00:02:16.369
( audience laughter )

00:02:16.369 --> 00:02:18.204
What the Olmec did,

00:02:18.204 --> 00:02:22.208
they actually would deform
the heads of their babies

00:02:22.208 --> 00:02:25.878
<i> in order to make them look
 more like cats.</i>

00:02:25.878 --> 00:02:29.649
<i>They believed that children born
 with Down Syndrome</i>

00:02:29.649 --> 00:02:31.450
<i> weren't anomalies</i>

00:02:31.450 --> 00:02:33.152
<i> they were almost God-like.</i>

00:02:33.152 --> 00:02:35.955
They believed that
Down Syndromes children

00:02:35.955 --> 00:02:37.891
looked like those cats.

00:02:37.891 --> 00:02:41.427
And were a cross
between a female,

00:02:41.427 --> 00:02:45.531
a human female mating with
a male jaguar.

00:02:45.531 --> 00:02:47.300
<i> Following the Olmecs,</i>

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:51.570
<i> the Maya carried jaguar
 iconography to new heights.</i>

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:55.374
<i> Always depicting jaguars
 never as just an animal,</i>

00:02:55.374 --> 00:02:57.610
<i> always as something more.</i>

00:02:57.610 --> 00:03:00.746
<i> Not just animal-human
 but beyond that.</i>

00:03:00.746 --> 00:03:04.350
Jaguars controlled the
world that the humans
couldn't control.

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:07.286
And if people wanted to control
the wild

00:03:07.286 --> 00:03:10.523
they had to somehow
do it through jaguars,

00:03:10.523 --> 00:03:13.458
become one with the jaguar.

00:03:13.458 --> 00:03:15.795
This was taken to its heights

00:03:15.795 --> 00:03:17.964
with jaguar shamans.

00:03:17.964 --> 00:03:21.567
<i> And one of the things
 that the jaguar shamans</i>

00:03:21.567 --> 00:03:23.836
<i> always sought to get,</i>

00:03:23.836 --> 00:03:27.273
<i> to absorb were the eyes
 of the jaguar.</i>

00:03:27.273 --> 00:03:29.041
<i> The eyes of a jaguar</i>

00:03:29.041 --> 00:03:32.978
<i>were believed to be able to see
 into the spirit world.</i>

00:03:32.978 --> 00:03:35.314
<i>Jaguars guarded the underworld,</i>

00:03:35.314 --> 00:03:38.150
<i> jaguars were a link to the
 spirit world.</i>

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:40.286
The modern day Maya
still believe

00:03:40.286 --> 00:03:42.955
if you wanted to see ghosts,

00:03:42.955 --> 00:03:45.591
you-- animals can see ghosts,

00:03:45.591 --> 00:03:48.360
you go and take
tears from an animal,

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:50.295
rub your finger in an
animal's eyes

00:03:50.295 --> 00:03:51.697
and then rub it on your eyes,

00:03:51.697 --> 00:03:53.766
it's one of the most
unhealthy practices

00:03:53.766 --> 00:03:55.434
( audience laughter )
in the world

00:03:55.434 --> 00:03:58.637
and you can see, see ghosts.

00:03:58.637 --> 00:04:01.441
Now all of this came to
an abrupt end

00:04:01.441 --> 00:04:02.909
in the 15th century

00:04:02.909 --> 00:04:05.644
<i> when the Spanish
 and Portuguese colonists</i>

00:04:05.644 --> 00:04:09.148
<i> came and conquered the
 New World.</i>

00:04:09.148 --> 00:04:12.418
<i> Now what the Spanish
 also brought with them</i>

00:04:12.418 --> 00:04:15.855
<i> were just big, dumb
 hunks of meat on a platter...</i>

00:04:15.855 --> 00:04:17.890
( audience laughter )
cattle.

00:04:17.890 --> 00:04:20.292
<i> And their version
 of cattle management</i>

00:04:20.292 --> 00:04:22.961
<i> was to allow large numbers
 of cattle</i>

00:04:22.961 --> 00:04:26.599
<i> to free range into wild areas.</i>

00:04:26.599 --> 00:04:29.269
<i> The jaguar had no idea
 what this animal was</i>

00:04:29.269 --> 00:04:31.970
<i> other than a big chunk of meat
 that stood there</i>

00:04:31.970 --> 00:04:34.940
as the jaguar swatted it and
knocked it down.

00:04:34.940 --> 00:04:36.408
( audience laughter )

00:04:36.408 --> 00:04:38.210
So, what happened,

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:41.614
jaguars were not seen
as semi-deities now anymore.

00:04:41.614 --> 00:04:43.249
<i> They were seen as vermin,</i>

00:04:43.249 --> 00:04:44.750
<i> seen as pests.</i>

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:46.853
<i> And the only way
 to get rid of them</i>

00:04:46.853 --> 00:04:48.387
<i> was to kill them.</i>

00:04:48.387 --> 00:04:52.191
<i>And you value them as trophies.</i>

00:04:52.191 --> 00:04:53.893
What really happened,

00:04:53.893 --> 00:04:57.530
which almost destroyed
the jaguar

00:04:57.530 --> 00:04:59.999
was the fashion industry.

00:04:59.999 --> 00:05:03.770
<i> In the 1960's,
 interestingly</i>

00:05:03.770 --> 00:05:06.505
<i> in the 1960's</i>

00:05:06.505 --> 00:05:10.409
Jackie Kennedy came out wearing
a leopard skin coat.

00:05:10.409 --> 00:05:12.078
In fact the man who created it

00:05:12.078 --> 00:05:14.980
for her,
Oleg Cassini later said

00:05:14.980 --> 00:05:19.151
it was one of the worst things
he ever did in his life.

00:05:19.151 --> 00:05:21.386
Because he had no idea
what it would lead to.

00:05:21.386 --> 00:05:23.722
<i>That spurred a fashion industry</i>

00:05:23.722 --> 00:05:26.925
<i> of spotted cat coats.</i>

00:05:26.925 --> 00:05:29.695
<i>Jaguars were becoming wiped out,</i>

00:05:29.695 --> 00:05:31.763
<i> as well as other spotted cats.</i>

00:05:31.763 --> 00:05:35.601
<i> That's a real leopard skin
 around that dog by the way.</i>

00:05:35.601 --> 00:05:40.306
What happened with this terrible
trade in spotted cat coats

00:05:40.306 --> 00:05:43.342
is that all the governments

00:05:43.342 --> 00:05:45.945
started to set up
new protected areas,

00:05:45.945 --> 00:05:47.713
started passing new laws,

00:05:47.713 --> 00:05:51.918
started banning jaguar hunting,
trade in jaguar skins.

00:05:51.918 --> 00:05:53.585
So this was good

00:05:53.585 --> 00:05:57.389
but now the jaguar
had to come back.

00:05:57.389 --> 00:05:59.057
<i> Okay,</i>

00:05:59.057 --> 00:06:01.861
<i> then a little boy named Alan
 steps into the scene</i>

00:06:01.861 --> 00:06:03.729
( audience laughter )

00:06:03.729 --> 00:06:06.599
<i> who knew nothing about what
 was happening with the jaguars</i>

00:06:06.599 --> 00:06:09.001
<i> and other spotted cats.</i>

00:06:09.001 --> 00:06:10.836
<i> I was a young man</i>

00:06:10.836 --> 00:06:15.541
<i> but I had been born
 with a debilitating stutter.</i>

00:06:15.541 --> 00:06:19.278
A really horrible stutter
to where I couldn't speak.

00:06:19.278 --> 00:06:21.546
It was called,
by the people at the time

00:06:21.546 --> 00:06:23.616
it was called "frozen mouth".

00:06:23.616 --> 00:06:25.317
They didn't know
what to do with me

00:06:25.317 --> 00:06:27.420
in the New York City
school systems,

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:30.022
they put me into
"special classes".

00:06:30.022 --> 00:06:31.356
They didn't know about

00:06:31.356 --> 00:06:34.893
dyslexia or ADHD or many things.

00:06:34.893 --> 00:06:36.495
I just shut down.

00:06:36.495 --> 00:06:38.865
So I didn't talk to any adults,

00:06:38.865 --> 00:06:43.202
which made them think
I was even more disturbed.

00:06:43.202 --> 00:06:45.204
But what I could do

00:06:45.204 --> 00:06:47.673
is I could talk to animals.

00:06:47.673 --> 00:06:48.974
I still stuttered,

00:06:48.974 --> 00:06:51.277
now we know stuttering
is not purely psychological,

00:06:51.277 --> 00:06:53.913
it's genetic.

00:06:53.913 --> 00:06:56.048
But I still stuttered
but I could,

00:06:56.048 --> 00:06:57.550
I could express myself,

00:06:57.550 --> 00:06:59.251
there was no expectation,

00:06:59.251 --> 00:07:02.154
no judging,
no speed-up, slow-down,

00:07:02.154 --> 00:07:04.423
no calm down or
finishing words for me,

00:07:04.423 --> 00:07:06.125
or anything like that.

00:07:06.125 --> 00:07:08.093
So, I could--
they became my life,

00:07:08.093 --> 00:07:10.263
they became my friends.

00:07:10.263 --> 00:07:12.031
And when I had bad weeks
at school,

00:07:12.031 --> 00:07:13.366
and there were many,

00:07:13.366 --> 00:07:16.168
because back then there weren't
these things against bullying

00:07:16.168 --> 00:07:17.970
and I was in a lot of fights.

00:07:17.970 --> 00:07:20.339
And I was always
in the principal's office.

00:07:20.339 --> 00:07:23.576
When there was a really bad
day at school

00:07:23.576 --> 00:07:24.977
or a bad week,

00:07:24.977 --> 00:07:28.647
my father would take me
to the Bronx Zoo.

00:07:28.647 --> 00:07:31.750
<i> And my favorite place
 at the Bronx Zoo</i>

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:34.252
<i> was what I called the
 "Big Cat House".</i>

00:07:34.252 --> 00:07:36.188
<i> Cage after cage after cage,</i>

00:07:36.188 --> 00:07:39.024
<i>concrete cage of lions, tigers,</i>

00:07:39.024 --> 00:07:40.592
<i> one lone jaguar.</i>

00:07:40.592 --> 00:07:43.895
And I knew as a kid, it was
really obvious to me as a kid,

00:07:43.895 --> 00:07:46.732
here these really big, strong,

00:07:46.732 --> 00:07:48.801
healthy, normal animals

00:07:48.801 --> 00:07:52.305
and they're locked inside
these jails,

00:07:52.305 --> 00:07:54.607
inside these cages,

00:07:54.607 --> 00:07:59.945
by human beings
who they could kill instantly.

00:07:59.945 --> 00:08:02.481
And the reason was

00:08:02.481 --> 00:08:04.549
because they didn't
have a voice.

00:08:04.549 --> 00:08:07.152
They didn't have a human voice.

00:08:07.152 --> 00:08:11.357
Imagine even today
if animals had a human voice

00:08:11.357 --> 00:08:13.125
how we would treat them.

00:08:13.125 --> 00:08:14.693
How many animals would we keep

00:08:14.693 --> 00:08:17.396
even in our nice zoos,
nice enclosures,

00:08:17.396 --> 00:08:19.966
if they actually said,
"Please, I don't
want to be here."

00:08:19.966 --> 00:08:23.535
Or, "Look, please,
stop feeding me that same food

00:08:23.535 --> 00:08:25.671
you're feeding me,
it's really terrible."

00:08:25.671 --> 00:08:26.839
How would we treat animals

00:08:26.839 --> 00:08:28.741
if-- and that's the
only difference.

00:08:28.741 --> 00:08:31.944
They can speak,
they communicate,
we all know that.

00:08:31.944 --> 00:08:33.846
But they don't have a
human voice.

00:08:33.846 --> 00:08:35.881
They were me, I was them.

00:08:35.881 --> 00:08:39.018
They became my haven.

00:08:39.018 --> 00:08:40.953
There was one lone jaguar.

00:08:40.953 --> 00:08:43.589
<i> This is a picture from
 my children's book.</i>

00:08:43.589 --> 00:08:45.925
<i> And I would always spend time
 with that lone jaguar</i>

00:08:45.925 --> 00:08:48.194
<i> because that jaguar,
 while all the other cats</i>

00:08:48.194 --> 00:08:50.629
<i> charged and growled and
 made vocalizations,</i>

00:08:50.629 --> 00:08:52.464
<i> that jaguar sat back,</i>

00:08:52.464 --> 00:08:55.467
<i> and just watched people
as if the people were in a cage</i>

00:08:55.467 --> 00:08:56.936
<i> and it was in charge.</i>

00:08:56.936 --> 00:08:59.070
<i> And I would stand there
 and talk to it.</i>

00:08:59.070 --> 00:09:00.973
And I would promise that jaguar

00:09:00.973 --> 00:09:03.509
and I had no idea
what I was promising.

00:09:03.509 --> 00:09:05.378
I was a very young child

00:09:05.378 --> 00:09:07.746
I had no idea what there
was in the greater world.

00:09:07.746 --> 00:09:11.050
All I knew was
my world was horrible.

00:09:11.050 --> 00:09:12.718
And I would promise him

00:09:12.718 --> 00:09:15.821
"if I ever got a voice

00:09:15.821 --> 00:09:18.791
I would be the voice
for the animals."

00:09:18.791 --> 00:09:21.493
Now I had no idea
what that meant.

00:09:21.493 --> 00:09:23.462
And it wasn't even about
the jaguars

00:09:23.462 --> 00:09:25.397
as much as it was about me.

00:09:25.397 --> 00:09:27.099
But I did make that promise

00:09:27.099 --> 00:09:30.036
every single time I stood by
the jaguar's cage

00:09:30.036 --> 00:09:31.403
or the tiger's cage.

00:09:31.403 --> 00:09:34.406
And I never forgot that promise.

00:09:34.406 --> 00:09:36.709
Fast forward

00:09:36.709 --> 00:09:39.478
20-- how many years,
I was about seven.

00:09:39.478 --> 00:09:42.348
Fast forward about 15 years

00:09:42.348 --> 00:09:43.815
or so in the future,

00:09:43.815 --> 00:09:46.051
went to graduate school,
studied eco--

00:09:46.051 --> 00:09:48.354
new courses called ecology

00:09:48.354 --> 00:09:51.523
and animal ecology,

00:09:51.523 --> 00:09:54.259
wildlife biology,

00:09:54.259 --> 00:09:56.662
and I meet my mentor
George Schaller.

00:09:56.662 --> 00:09:59.632
<i> I end up being sent by
 George Schaller</i>

00:09:59.632 --> 00:10:02.701
<i> to this newly independent
 country called Belize</i>

00:10:02.701 --> 00:10:04.636
<i> in 1981.</i>

00:10:04.636 --> 00:10:07.606
<i> In order to try to see</i>

00:10:07.606 --> 00:10:10.442
<i> why there are jaguars
 being actually hit</i>

00:10:10.442 --> 00:10:14.146
<i> on the one dirt road
 through the entire country.</i>

00:10:14.146 --> 00:10:15.981
Then when that worked out

00:10:15.981 --> 00:10:18.350
he said, "Would you like to
go back for a few years

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:20.352
and actually try to
capture them,

00:10:20.352 --> 00:10:21.954
study them, radio-collar them?

00:10:21.954 --> 00:10:23.589
Do what nobody has ever done

00:10:23.589 --> 00:10:26.058
in the rainforest habitat."

00:10:26.058 --> 00:10:27.292
And I said, "Absolutely."

00:10:27.292 --> 00:10:29.728
I had no idea
how I'd catch jaguars.

00:10:29.728 --> 00:10:31.763
( audience laughter )
I had no idea

00:10:31.763 --> 00:10:35.167
at first where even Belize was
when he first told me.

00:10:35.167 --> 00:10:37.836
<i> So I went down.
 Now catching jaguars
 wasn't easy.</i>

00:10:37.836 --> 00:10:39.071
<i> I didn't know how at first.</i>

00:10:39.071 --> 00:10:41.706
<i> The first time I built
 wooden traps two-by-fours,</i>

00:10:41.706 --> 00:10:43.308
<i> I actually caught a
 black jaguar.</i>

00:10:43.308 --> 00:10:46.311
<i> It chewed and busted out of my
 two-by-four traps.</i>

00:10:46.311 --> 00:10:47.879
<i> Later I learnt from
 the Mennonites</i>

00:10:47.879 --> 00:10:49.715
<i> how to build
 an iron rebar trap.</i>

00:10:49.715 --> 00:10:52.618
<i> I captured jaguars,
 radio-collared them,</i>

00:10:52.618 --> 00:10:53.619
<i> learned how to drug,</i>

00:10:53.819 --> 00:10:56.421
<i> back then we didn't have vets
 showing us any of this,</i>

00:10:56.421 --> 00:10:59.325
<i> which wasn't good.
 It was very hit or miss.</i>

00:10:59.325 --> 00:11:01.326
I mean, I used safe drugs

00:11:01.326 --> 00:11:03.595
but jaguars weren't
always fully asleep.

00:11:03.595 --> 00:11:04.630
( audience laughter )

00:11:04.630 --> 00:11:06.465
This was difficult,

00:11:06.465 --> 00:11:09.502
it was dangerous and
it was great.

00:11:09.502 --> 00:11:10.902
It was my life.

00:11:10.902 --> 00:11:13.105
This was what I was meant for.

00:11:13.105 --> 00:11:15.641
<i> One of the things
 which I noticed right away,</i>

00:11:15.641 --> 00:11:17.476
<i> in the early days is</i>

00:11:17.476 --> 00:11:19.478
<i> how jaguars have a voice.</i>

00:11:19.478 --> 00:11:21.313
<i> How they do talk,</i>

00:11:21.313 --> 00:11:22.448
<i> they communicate</i>

00:11:22.448 --> 00:11:25.818
<i> with incredible amounts of
 different signals,</i>

00:11:25.818 --> 00:11:28.453
<i> scratches,
 scrapes, fecal deposits,</i>

